bug.short_desc: Possible synchronization/refresh issue with bugzilla connector

long_desc.thetext:
I'm not sure under what circumstances this happens, or even how to repeat it, but I'll try to describe the series of events as closely as possible:
I was trying to add a comment to Bug#142039 I saved and closed the issue I saw the arrow next to the issue in the task list view, representing pending outgoing changes The progress view had the synchronization process going for about 10 minutes So I closed Eclipse and re-opened it However, the arrow was still next to the issue, and the process view was still going So I right-clicked on the issue in the task list, and selected "synchronize" At this point, it said that my copy of the issue contained a conflict with what was on the server Having already saved my comment to a file, I let Mylar override my local copy Much to my surprise, the server's override contained my comment
So I'm guessing somewhere along the way my comment *was* posted to the server, but Mylar didn't successfully record/update that status locally? Eh, but as I think about it, if the server did actually get my update but Mylar "lost" that status, wouldn't Mylar have then found an update on the server and try to download it / merge it into my local copy?
Perhaps these operations were meant to be done serially, and so since the upload was hanging (across to the Process view), the download never started?
I actually -just- had this happen to me. In my situation there was a synchronization job that was pending as well...

Fixed. Retrieval of the posted bug was failing due to pending query synchronizations. I've loosened scheduling policy to allow task synchronization when query synchronization is pending. Although my testing shows improvement, this problem may arise from other circumstances so please re-open if you experience this after upgrading to tonight's developer build. In addition bugs affected by submission (dependson etc) are no longer immediately synchronized as this causes a double synchronization of the submitted task and the others will be synchronized later in background anyway.

bug.short_desc: StateHelper needs a way to get system packages from getVisiblePackages

long_desc.thetext:
The StateHelper.getVisiblePackages currently excludes packages that are available from the Execution Environment as exports from the system bundle (org.eclipse.osgi).
There is a need in PDE to get the execution environment packages that are visible from a bundle.

Created an attachment (id=54099) patch
This patch adds a new method getVisiblePackages(BundleDescription bundle, int options);
The only supported option is VISIBLE_INCLUDE_EE_PACKAGES. To get all visible packages from a bundle including the packages from the Execution Environment you call
stateHelper.getVisiblePackages(bundle, StateHelper.VISIBLE_INCLUDE_EE_PACKAGES)
You can tell an ExportPackageDescription is an Execution Environment package by checking the "x-equinox-ee" directive on the export. For example:
ExportPackageDescription exportedPackage = .... boolean isEEPackage = ((Integer) exportedpacakge.getDirective("x-equinox-ee")).intValue() >= 0;
The "x-equinox-ee" directive is an internal directive the resolver uses to distinguish EE packages. If the value is >= 0 then the package is an EE package. A value of -1 indicates it is a normal exported package. We can use this for now to determine which packages are EE packages.

Unfortunately in UA we have no control over the preference dialog. The proper way to control this, I believe, is to opt in. That is, if you want the preference page, add the extension, if not, don't.
The problem is that we're forcing you to opt in by putting the extension in org.eclipse.platform. I believe it should instead be in org.eclipse.sdk, which is specific to the eclipse SDK and not meant for any other product.
Dejan do you agree?

There are several other related problems in the org.eclipse.platform plug-in, including it's declaration of an "ide" product in the org.eclipse.core.runtime.products extension point, and its contribution of an introData.xml file (and introContent/extensionContent files). Shouldn't those be contributed in the SDK plug-in as well?
(In reply to comment #1) > The problem is that we're forcing you to opt in by putting the extension in > org.eclipse.platform. I believe it should instead be in org.eclipse.sdk, which > is specific to the eclipse SDK and not meant for any other product. > Dejan do you agree?

The reason it is in org.eclipse.platform.ide product is because Callisto is built on top of the platform, not ide. We wanted to start by installing the bare platform, and build it up by adding IDE, SDK, GEF, EMF etc. As you add Callisto layers, Welcome content increases. For this reason, the platform is a 'product' in its own right.

But should the platform really be a product?
The platform as a product seems to be in conflict with this stated purpose, "The Eclipse Platform subproject provides the core frameworks and services upon which all plug-in extensions are created."
From: http://www.eclipse.org/platform/overview.php
Consider this from a "product" perspective; if the platform is a product itself, then any product built on the platform would actually be just a (platform) product extension, unless it re-implemented the platform, which doesn't make sense.
You know, the platform plug-in could contribute an intro config extension without being a product itself.
Correct, but installing only Eclipse platform, or Eclipse + JDT would be Welcome-less otherwise.

In reply to comment 4, platform being the product by itself is not making everything else on top of it an extension. At any point in the layered 'cake' you can create another product and launch your application as such. It is possible to have multiple products defined for the same pool of plug-ins. The launch point that starts eclipse will define which product you are starting with, and that will affect your branding, splash, welcome, preferences and other product-related attributes.

There is already code in WorkbenchWindow to restore the workbench to a maximised state - see saveState() and restoreState() references to IWorkbenchConstants.TAG_MAXIMIZED which is want we want I think. The problem lies in window events. When maximising a window on OS X, the Workbench window is sent a resize event, not a maximise event. The event kind is OS.kEventWindowBoundsChanged which finds its way to WorkbenchWindow.trackShellResize which in turn records the bounds of the shell and sets the field 'asMaximizedState' to false. So the maximised state of the workbench window is not recorded in the saveState() method.

When a shell is created it sets attributes including OS.kWindowFullZoomAttribute which is actually OS.kWindowVerticalZoomAttribute | OS.kWindowHorizontalZoomAttribute. I think I need to read these attributes if possible but cannot see how to do it.

Hi Erkki and Bob,
I can't reproduce this problem consistently either.
I've seen the PDE get confused on occasion by the combination of Require-Bundle and the use of reexport (which org.eclipse.ecf bundle does for org.eclipse.ecf.identity...and both org.eclipse.ecf and org.eclipse.ecf.identity have classes for package org.eclipse.ecf.core.util).
The reason for splitting these classes from package org.eclipse.ecf.core.util across bundles is that I wanted to make it possible for people to use org.eclipse.ecf.identity *without* org.eclipse.ecf, and so the classes from org.eclipse.ecf.core.util that are in the org.eclipse.ecf.identity bundle are only those needed by the org.eclipse.ecf.identity bundle).
One suggestion though...don't have *two* dependencies on both the org.eclipse.ecf.identity and org.eclipse.ecf...just add one dependency on org.eclipse.ecf...and it will reexport any/all classes from org.eclipse.ecf.identity that are needed.
I'm very hesitant to move packages/classes around again for this, as it wasn't a mistake in organization...rather it was intended to be that way so that identity could be used separately from ECF if that was all that was desired/required. Also...sharing packages across bundles is done frequently in the platform (e.g. org.eclipse.core.runtime classes come from several different bundles) so I'm quite confident that it will work for ECF.
Anyway...I'm not going to mark this bug resolved until we have some further discussion among at least Bob and Erkki and I (and anyone else interested). Bob please let everyone know if things can't be set right for whatever reason (Bob).

bug.short_desc: Presentation of the BPMN modeler

long_desc.thetext:
This article is a short tutorial which shows the BPMN modeler of the STP project.
It will present how to draw a business process. To do so it will present the different shapes that are made available to the user: tasks, subprocesses, events and gateways.
It will show how to orchestrate those elements into sequences and flows and produce a valid business process.
This article is related to the EclipseCon tutorial proposal: http://eclipsezilla.eclipsecon.org/show_bug.cgi?id=3595
It should be considered as a written form of the tutorial.
+1 sounds interesting. An outline (possibly based on your presentation) would be a great next step.

This article will not cover the complete tutorial we will make for EclipseCon, neither will the tutorial cover the full article.
I (and Hugues) just don't have time to work on this until January.
Keep updated!
For now, we have some bits of documentation on the wiki: http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/STP_Sub-project_specific_pages

bug.short_desc: Add a "Open Remote Task" dialog

long_desc.thetext:
One thing that I didn't understand when I started to use Mylar is the concept that to be able to simply see a bug report I have to add it to the task list, either by using "add existing task" or by creating a query.
This is confusing to newbies and hard to people who don't want to follow the Mylar workflow (let's say someone just wants a bugzilla plugin for Eclipse) or simply wants to browse to an arbitrary bug.
I propose to create a "Open Remote Task" dialog, like "Open Task", where you can enter the bug ID and select the repository in a list.
Also, I think it can substitute the (confusing) "Add Existing Task" with advantages, by having some checkbox at bottom: "Add to task list".
Having it checked, it would have the same behavior the "Add Existing Task" has, but in just one dialog (no 2 page wizard).
Having it unchecked, it would just open the remote bug editor, like when you click on a bug hyperlink.
Another thing I miss on the current "Add Existing Task" wizard, and that we can include on this dialog is a combobox to optionally select in what category the bug should be added.
At last, it can be implemented as a command, so we can assign a shortcut key (any ideas on what can be the key sequence?).
I'm not sure if this is what Eugene suggests on item 3 of bug#152173 (Eugene? can you hear me? :)

bug.short_desc: Ctrl+Right_Shift+Left on Rename refactoring dialog changes text direction

long_desc.thetext:
Steps to reproduce:
- Invoke the Rename Refactoring (Alt+Shift+R) on a local variable or a type name. - With the cursor on the "new name" text field, type Ctrl+Shift+Left Arrow (it has to be the right-side Ctrl and Shift keys, NOT the left ones). - After that the text will be right aligned, and the text direction and navigation will be inverted, from right to left.
It also happens on other JDT dialogs, like "Open Type" or "Extract Local Variable".

Wheew, scary Windows "feature"!
When you press Ctrl+Right_Shift, then Windows switches the input mode to "right to left". I can reproduce that in every text widget (ControlExample, but also in the address field of the Internet Explorer). To switch back to "left to right", you have to press Ctrl+Left_Shift.
On all the fields you mentioned, we install a KeyListener and use our custom (CamelCase-aware) word selection methods for Java names. We set KeyEvent#doit to false in this case.
Unfortunately, SWT does not seem to catch the subsequent keyUp event for Ctrl+Shift, leading to the behavior you observe.

(In reply to comment #2) > To switch back to "left to > right", you have to press Ctrl+Left_Shift. >
Humm... good to see it has a workaround to this "feature", since actually cancel the operation when it happens.
Yes, it is scary because I have the habit to use Right_Ctrl+Right_Shift+Left keys to camel-case-select (it is practical because I can use only my right hand).
BTW, do you know if there is some place to disable this lovely "feature" on Windows?

> BTW, do you know if there is some place to disable this lovely "feature" on > Windows? Control Panel > Regional and Language Options > Languages tab: Disable the checkboxes in 'Supplemental language support' and restart Windows.
Felipe, can you confirm that this is happening?

Steve, this is native windows behaviour. The user can disable this option in the control-panel. Note, this option is off by default, the user only gets this feature when he enables support for right-to-left languages.
Consider closing this problem report as wontfix.

Just to clarify: I don't think you should block Ctrl+Right_Shift from switching direction.
It's just problematic that setting event.doit=false for the keyDown event for Ctrl+Right_Shift+Arrow_Left still lets the keyUp event Ctrl+Right_Shift go out to Windows to execute its evil intentions.

This is not bug, the user has configured the OS to changed the direction of text widget when the ctrl+right_shift is pressed. SWT gets this feature for free for being native.
I don't think you should put any hack in your code, neither should us put one in SWT (this would very much upset the developers in Egypt and Israel).
IMO you should explaing to your client how to use Windows Control Panel to disable this feature or how to assign its shortcut to something else.
Felipe, is this a WONTFIX for SWT?

No, the problem is NOT that Ctrl+Shift changes the direction!
The problem is that the text direction changes if Ctrl+Shift+something is handled with "e.doit = false". In that scenario, the user did NOT press Ctrl+Shift, so he should NOT get a direction change.
Of course, nobody should ever block Ctrl+Shift. It should just not occur as a side effect.

Markus, I'm confused, you said: "The problem is that the text direction changes if Ctrl+Shift+something is handled with "e.doit = false". In that scenario, the user did NOT press Ctrl+Shift, so he should NOT get a direction change."
Means that the user actions were: press CTRL and hold press SHIFT and hold (there, the direction changes here in this WM_KEYDOWN) press "something" (at this point the direction changed already does not matter what we do to the event)
So, the user DID press CTRL+SHIFT in order to compose CTRL+SHIFT+something.
am I missing something obvious here ?

We're getting to the point ;-)
> Means that the user actions were: > press CTRL and hold > press SHIFT and hold (there, the direction changes here in this WM_KEYDOWN) No, please try it. You can press and hold CTRL+RIGHT_SHIFT and the direction does not change.
> press "something" (at this point the direction changed already does not matter > what we do to the event) "something" is e.g. ARROW_RIGHT => this will select the next word.
The key is that Windows only interprets CTRL+SHIFT as direction change if no key was pressed afterwards. As soon as any third key has been pressed, Windows never changes the direction.
My code says "e.doit = false", which tells SWT (and Windows) that I don't want the default behavior for that keystroke. Nevertheless, the third key really has been pressed, so the direction change should be canceled.

> The key is that Windows only interprets CTRL+SHIFT as direction change if no > key was pressed afterwards. As soon as any third key has been pressed, Windows > never changes the direction.
Correct. I get it now.
> My code says "e.doit = false", which tells SWT (and Windows) that I don't want > the default behavior for that keystroke. Nevertheless, the third key really has > been pressed, so the direction change should be canceled.
Well, at this point you have to agree with me that you are doing this to yourself. You know windows has to process the third key so it doesn't change direction on you. But at the same time you want windows not to process the key.
As far as I know, we (SWT) can propagate the key to windows (call windowProc) or not (according to event.doit). I don't think we can fix this problem. Sorry.
Felipe, please give me a demo and make me understand why this is an SWT bug.
> Felipe, please give me a demo and make me understand why this is an SWT bug. I think it's a Windows bug, but SWT would be the best place for a workaround.

bug.short_desc: [JVMTI Client] Execution Time Analysis does not work after Memory Analysis or Thread Analysis

long_desc.thetext:
If you launch the JVMTI Profiler's Memory Analysis or Thread Analysis collectors, you can no longer use the Execution Time Analysis collectors.
Steps to reproduce ================== 1. From the Monitor tab, select either the Heap Analysis or Thread Analysis JVMTI collectors and execute a profiling session. 2. When done, launch a new session and select the Execution Time Analysis JVMTI collector. No data will appear in the profiling perspective.
Problem Analysis ================ The problem is in the launch() method of the org.eclipse.tptp.platform.jvmti.client.internal.launcher.TIDelegateHelper class: by default, the string in the TI_JVM_FLAG static field contains the options to launch the JVMTI Call Graph profiler (CGProf). When the user selects either the Thread Analysis or Heap Analysis options, the value of the TI_JVM_FLAG is overwritten with the options to launch the selected profiler (either HeapProf or ThreadProf). However, there is no code to set this variable back to launching CGProf in case the user selects Execution Time Analysis.
Due to problems in configuring the build environment, I cannot fix, test this defect, and submit a patch. I suggest someone from the UI group will take an ownership and fix this.

long_desc.thetext:
Image of the behavior can be found here:
http://picasaweb.google.com/aaronmcohen/TestCase/photo#4999174879417335826

The layout manager works as designed. Unlike GridLayout, TableWrapLayout places controls top to bottom in a natural flow similar to Web tables. The composite with this layout will be as tall as needed to fit all the control (including wrapped text for which this layout has been designed). Vertical fill is there only for cases where one control spans more than one rows. In this case, you can control whether you want this control to fill the entire multi-row space or just as much as needed for its natural size.
